   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "84b488ee",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "InvoiceNo that starts with the letter 'C' indicates a canceled transaction. We will delete this data, because we will analyze only successful transactions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "2279148a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#Delete canceled transaction rows\n",
    "df = df[~df['InvoiceNo'].str.contains('C')]"
   ]
  },

       "      <td>0.000000</td>\n",
       "    </tr>\n",
       "    <tr>\n",
       "      <th>7</th>\n",
       "      <td>Country</td>\n",
       "      <td>0</td>\n",
       "      <td>0.000000</td>\n",
       "    </tr>\n",
       "  </tbody>\n",
       "</table>\n",
       "</div>"
      ],
      "text/plain": [
       "      variable  number_of_missing  percentage_of_missing\n",
       "0   CustomerID             134697              25.289465\n",
       "1  Description               1454               0.272990\n",
       "2    InvoiceNo                  0               0.000000\n",
       "3    StockCode                  0               0.000000\n",
       "4     Quantity                  0               0.000000\n",
       "5  InvoiceDate                  0               0.000000\n",
       "6    UnitPrice                  0               0.000000\n",
       "7      Country                  0               0.000000"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 18,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "def missingvalue(data):\n",
    "    missing_value = data.isnull().sum(axis = 0).reset_index()\n",
    "    missing_value.columns = ['variable', 'number_of_missing']\n",
    "    missing_value['percentage_of_missing'] = (missing_value['number_of_missing'])/data.shape[0]*100\n",
    "    mv = missing_value.sort_values('percentage_of_missing', ascending = False).reset_index(drop=True)\n",
    "    return mv\n",
    "missingvalue(df)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "id": "4591bfd6",

   "outputs": [],

   ],
   "source": [
    "group = df.groupby('CustomerID')['InvoiceMonth']\n",
    "df['CohortMonth'] = group.transform('min')\n",
    "df"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 36,
   "id": "ac9c0f64",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def date(data, column):\n",
    "    year = data[column].dt.year\n",
    "    month = data[column].dt.month\n",
    "    day = data[column].dt.day\n",
    "    return year, month, day"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 37,
   "id": "40d503bb",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "invoice_year, invoice_month, _ = date(df, 'InvoiceMonth')\n",
    "cohort_year, cohort_month, _ = date(df, 'CohortMonth')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2e43f355",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "Furthermore, the month difference will be calculated between the first customer shopping at the retail store and the invoice time.\n",
    "Difference in years and months"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 38,
   "id": "b74fad6b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "diff_year = invoice_year - cohort_year\n",
    "diff_month = invoice_month - cohort_month"
   ]
  },

    "count_cohort_time = df.groupby(['CohortMonth', 'IndexTime'])['CustomerID'].apply(pd.Series.nunique)\n",
    "count_cohort_time = count_cohort_time.reset_index()\n",
    "cohort_time_table = count_cohort_time.pivot(index='CohortMonth', columns='IndexTime', values='CustomerID')\n",
    "cohort_time_table"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f90a1eb6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Customer Retention Rate"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5a0726c1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Customer retention is a very useful metric to understand how many of all the customers are still active. Customer retention rate designates the percentage of customers the company has retained over a given time period. Retention rate is a reverse side of churn rate, which shows the percentage of customers a company has lost over a specific period"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 43,
   "id": "1e574acd",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1152x576 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "cohort_size = cohort_time_table.iloc[:,0]\n",
    "#Divide all values in the cohort_time_table by cohort_size\n",
    "retention = cohort_time_table.divide(cohort_size, axis = 0)\n",
    "retention.index = retention.index.strftime('%Y-%m')\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize= (16,8))\n",
    "ax = sns.heatmap(data = retention, annot = True, annot_kws={\"size\":10}, vmin = 0.0, vmax = 0.5, fmt = '.0%', cmap = 'YlGnBu')\n",
    "plt.title('Customer Retention Time')\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "rfm_cust = df.groupby('CustomerID').agg({\n",
    "    'InvoiceDate': lambda x: (analysis_date - x.max()).days,\n",
    "    'InvoiceNo': 'count',\n",
    "    'TotalPrice': 'sum'})\n",
    "rfm_cust.rename(columns= {'InvoiceDate':'Recency',\n",
    "                         'InvoiceNo':'Frequency',\n",
    "                         'TotalPrice':'Monetary'}, inplace = True)\n",
    "rfm_cust"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "#1 is the best and 4 is the worst\n",
    "r_labels = range(1,5) #The longer the customer last purchase, the worse it is\n",
    "f_labels = range(4,0,-1) #The more purchases the customer makes, the better it is\n",
    "m_labels = range(4,0,-1) #The more money the customer spends, the better it is\n",
    "\n",
    "r_quartiles = pd.qcut(rfm_cust['Recency'], q=4, labels=r_labels)\n",
    "f_quartiles = pd.qcut(rfm_cust['Frequency'], q=4, labels=f_labels)\n",
    "m_quartiles = pd.qcut(rfm_cust['Monetary'], q=4, labels=m_labels)\n",
    "\n",
    "rfm_cust = rfm_cust.assign(R = r_quartiles.values, F = f_quartiles.values, M = m_quartiles.values)\n",
    "\n",
    "rfm_cust"
   ]

    "def join_rfm(x):\n",
    "    return str(x['R']) + str(x['F']) + str(x['M'])\n",
    "rfm_cust['RFM_Segment'] = rfm_cust.apply(join_rfm, axis=1)\n",
    "rfm_cust['RFM_Score'] = rfm_cust[['R', 'F', 'M']].sum(axis=1)\n",
    "rfm_cust.head()"
   ]

    "1.Symmetric distribution of variables (not skewed)   \n",
    "2.Variables with same average values   \n",

    "\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "    print('Skewness value of data {}: {}'.format(column, r_skew))"
   ]

   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d6f51124",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As a general rule of thumb:  \n",
    "\n",
    "If the skewness is between -0.5 and 0.5, the data are fairly symmetrical.\n",
    "If the skewness is between -1 and -0.5(negatively skewed) or between 0.5 and 1(positively skewed), the data are moderately skewed.\n",
    "If the skewness is less than -1(negatively skewed) or greater than 1(positively skewed), the data are highly skewed.\n",
    "\n",
    "From the general rule of thumb, it can be concluded that data Recency, Frequency, and Monetary are highly positive skew. So, the data must be transformed (Data Transformation) to make it into a normal distribution."
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "power = PowerTransformer().fit(rfm_norm)\n",
    "rfm_transform =power.transform(rfm_norm)\n",
    "\n",
    "#Standard Scaler to Scale the data\n",
    "scaler = StandardScaler().fit(rfm_transform)\n",
    "rfm_transform = scaler.transform(rfm_transform)\n",
    "\n",
    "rfm_transform =pd.DataFrame(rfm_transform, index=rfm_norm.index, columns=rfm_norm.columns)\n",
    "print('These are the mean value after data transformation:')\n",
    "rfm_transform.describe()"
   ]

    "def rfm_dist_transform(column):\n",
    "    r_skew_transform = rfm_transform[column].skew()\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.rcParams['font.size']=13\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))\n",
    "    sns.distplot(rfm_transform[column], color = 'g', kde_kws={\"color\": \"k\"})\n",
    "    plt.title('{} Distribution after Data Transformation'.format(column))\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "    print('Skewness value of data {} after data transformation: {}'.format(column, r_skew_transform))"
   ]

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since the skewness values are between -0.5 to 0.5, or close to 0, it can be assumed that the RFM data has a normal distribution."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ac5198f9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Determining the number of clusters"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "88643155",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Elbow Method"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9fb57051",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The elbow method runs k-means clustering on the dataset for a range of values for k (say from 1-10) and for each value of k, calculate the sum of squared errors (SSE). The idea of elbow method is to choose K at SSE decreases abruptly."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 67,
   "id": "cd84b14c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 720x504 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#Elbow Method\n",
    "\n",
    "inertia=[]\n",
    "cl = 15\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(1,cl+1):\n",
    "    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters= i, init='k-means++', random_state=42)\n",
    "    kmeans.fit(rfm_transform)\n",
    "    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_) #sum of squared distances to closest cluster center\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "fig,ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "fig.set_size_inches(10, 7)\n",
    "plt.rcParams['font.size']=16\n",
    "plt.plot(range(1,cl+1), inertia, 'o-', color = 'g')\n",
    "plt.xticks(np.arange(0, 15, 1.0))\n",
    "plt.title('The Elbow Method')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Number of of Clusters (k)')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Sum of Squared Distances')\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "72f80186",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Silhouette Analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1f176704",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Silhouette displays a measure of how close each point in one cluster is to points in the neighbouring clusters. Silhouette score has a range of [-1, 1]\n",
    "\n",
    "* A value near +1 indicate that the sample is far away from the neighbouring clusters.\n",
    "* A value of 0 indicates that the sample is on or very close to the decision boundary between two neighbouring clusters.\n",
    "* Negative values indicate that those samples might have been assigned to the wrong cluster."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 68,
   "id": "6321f375",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "For n_clusters = 2 The average silhouette_score is : 0.396689892885645\n",
      "For n_clusters = 3 The average silhouette_score is : 0.29935070361583976\n",
      "For n_clusters = 4 The average silhouette_score is : 0.30417720917225627\n",
      "For n_clusters = 5 The average silhouette_score is : 0.27881749014909163\n",
      "For n_clusters = 6 The average silhouette_score is : 0.277274890389003\n"

    "range_n_clusters = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6]\n",
    "\n",
    "for n_clusters in range_n_clusters:\n",
    "    # Create a subplot with 1 row and 2 columns\n",
    "    fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3, ax4) = plt.subplots(1, 4)\n",
    "    fig.set_size_inches(30, 7)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # The 1st subplot is the silhouette plot\n",
    "    # The silhouette coefficient can range from -1, 1 but in this example all\n",
    "    # lie within [-0.1, 1]\n",
    "    ax1.set_xlim([-0.1, 1])\n",
    "    # The (n_clusters+1)*10 is for inserting blank space between silhouette\n",
    "    # plots of individual clusters, to demarcate them clearly.\n",
    "    ax1.set_ylim([0, len(rfm_transform) + (n_clusters + 1) * 10])\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Initialize the clusterer with n_clusters value and a random generator\n",
    "    # seed of 10 for reproducibility.\n",
    "    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state=10)\n",
    "    cluster_labels = clusterer.fit_predict(rfm_transform)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # The silhouette_score gives the average value for all the samples.\n",
    "    # This gives a perspective into the density and separation of the formed\n",
    "    # clusters\n",
    "    silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(rfm_transform, cluster_labels)\n",
    "    print(\"For n_clusters =\", n_clusters,\n",
    "          \"The average silhouette_score is :\", silhouette_avg)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Compute the silhouette scores for each sample\n",
    "    sample_silhouette_values = silhouette_samples(rfm_transform, cluster_labels)\n",
    "\n",
    "    y_lower = 10\n",
    "    for i in range(n_clusters):\n",
    "        # Aggregate the silhouette scores for samples belonging to\n",
    "        # cluster i, and sort them\n",
    "        ith_cluster_silhouette_values = \\\n",
    "            sample_silhouette_values[cluster_labels == i]\n",
    "\n",
    "        ith_cluster_silhouette_values.sort()\n",
    "\n",
    "        size_cluster_i = ith_cluster_silhouette_values.shape[0]\n",
    "        y_upper = y_lower + size_cluster_i\n",
    "\n",
    "        color = cm.rainbow(float(i) / n_clusters)\n",
    "        ax1.fill_betweenx(np.arange(y_lower, y_upper),\n",
    "                          0, ith_cluster_silhouette_values,\n",
    "                          facecolor=color, edgecolor=color, alpha=0.7)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Label the silhouette plots with their cluster numbers at the middle\n",
    "        ax1.text(-0.05, y_lower + 0.5 * size_cluster_i, str(i))\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Compute the new y_lower for next plot\n",
    "        y_lower = y_upper + 10  # 10 for the 0 samples\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax1.set_title(\"The silhouette plot for the various clusters.\")\n",
    "    ax1.set_xlabel(\"The silhouette coefficient values\")\n",
    "    ax1.set_ylabel(\"Cluster label\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # The vertical line for average silhouette score of all the values\n",
    "    ax1.axvline(x=silhouette_avg, color=\"red\", linestyle=\"--\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax1.set_yticks([])  # Clear the yaxis labels / ticks\n",
    "    ax1.set_xticks([-0.1, 0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1])\n",
    "\n",
    "    # 2nd Plot showing the actual clusters formed\n",
    "    colors = cm.rainbow(cluster_labels.astype(float) / n_clusters)\n",
    "    ax2.scatter(rfm_transform['Monetary'], rfm_transform['Recency'], marker='.', s=30, lw=0, alpha=0.7,\n",
    "                c=colors, edgecolor='k')\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Labeling the clusters\n",
    "    centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_\n",
    "    # Draw white circles at cluster centers\n",
    "    ax2.scatter(centers[:, 2], centers[:, 0], marker='o',\n",
    "                c=\"white\", alpha=1, s=200, edgecolor='k')\n",
    "\n",
    "    for i, c in enumerate(centers):\n",
    "        ax2.scatter(c[2], c[0], marker='$%d$' % i, alpha=1,\n",
    "                    s=50, edgecolor='k')\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax2.set_title(\"The visualization of the clustered data.\")\n",
    "    ax2.set_xlabel(\"Shopping Frequency\")\n",
    "    ax2.set_ylabel(\"Shopping Amount\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.suptitle((\"Silhouette analysis for KMeans clustering on sample data \"\n",
    "                  \"with n_clusters = %d\" % n_clusters),\n",
    "                 fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')\n",
    "    \n",
    "        # 3nd Plot showing the actual clusters formed\n",
    "    colors = cm.rainbow(cluster_labels.astype(float) / n_clusters)\n",
    "    ax3.scatter(rfm_transform['Frequency'], rfm_transform['Recency'], marker='.', s=30, lw=0, alpha=0.7,\n",
    "                c=colors, edgecolor='k')\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Labeling the clusters\n",
    "    centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a5a55036",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We will choose 4 clusters based on the elbow method, because there is no significant decrease in sum of squared distance or SSE after 4 clusters. Based on the silhouette analysis, the silhouette_score that is close to 1 is for the number of clusters 2 and 4.By combining the elbow method and silhouette analysis, the number of clusters 4 is selected."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7af07e11",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## KMeans Clustering"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "1216cc12",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "n = 4\n",
    "\n",
    "model = KMeans(n_clusters=n,init='k-means++',max_iter=300, n_init=10, random_state=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "#fit the data\n",
    "model_kmeans = model.fit(rfm_transform)\n",
    "\n",
    "# These are our fitted labels for clusters -- the first cluster has label 0, and the second has label 1.\n",
    "labels = model_kmeans.labels_\n",
    "\n",
    "centers = model_kmeans.cluster_centers_\n",
    "\n",
    "#Append labels/clusters to scaled and original dataframe\n",
    "rfm_cust['Cluster'] = labels\n",
    "clusters_seg = pd.DataFrame(rfm_transform,columns=['Recency','Frequency','Monetary'])\n",
    "clusters_seg['Cluster'] = labels+1\n",
    "\n",
    "clusters = []\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(0,n):\n",
    "    clusters.append(rfm_cust[rfm_cust['Cluster']==i])\n",
    "\n",
    "values = power.inverse_transform(scaler.inverse_transform(centers))\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(0,n):\n",
    "    print('-----CLUSTER {}-----'.format(i+1))\n",
    "    print('Number of Customers: {}'.format(clusters[i].shape[0]))\n",
    "    print('(Recency)Last Day Shopping: {:4.0f}'.format(values[i][0]))\n",
    "    print('(Frec)Purchases Frequency : {:4.0f}'.format(values[i][1]))\n",
    "    print('(Monetary)Total purchases: £{:6.2f}\\n'.format(values[i][2]))"
   ]
  },

    "## Snake plot\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "47ede5a3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "* Market research technique to compare different segments\n",
    "* Visual representation of each segment's attributes"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 73,
   "id": "a993e2dc",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1008x720 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "data_melt = pd.melt(rfm_transform.reset_index(), id_vars=['CustomerID','Cluster'], value_vars=['Recency','Frequency','Monetary'], var_name='Attribute', value_name='Value')\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(14,10))\n",
    "plt.title('Snake plot of standardized variables')\n",
    "ax = sns.lineplot(x='Attribute', y='Value', hue='Cluster',palette=['tomato','cornflowerblue','violet','mediumseagreen'], data=data_melt, sort=False)\n",
    "ax.legend(['1','2','3','4'])\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "128f92cb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The lower the Recency value, the better it is. The higher the Frequency and Monetary values, the better it is."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "94d631e0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,8))\n",
    "ax=Axes3D(fig)\n",
    "ax.scatter(rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==0]['Recency'],rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==0]['Frequency'],rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==0]['Monetary'],color='tomato', label='Cluster 1')\n",
    "ax.scatter(rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==1]['Recency'],rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==1]['Frequency'],rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==1]['Monetary'],color='cornflowerblue', label='Cluster 2')\n",
    "ax.scatter(rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==2]['Recency'],rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==2]['Frequency'],rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==2]['Monetary'],color='violet', label='Cluster 3')\n",
    "ax.scatter(rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==3]['Recency'],rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==3]['Frequency'],rfm_transform[rfm_transform['Cluster']==3]['Monetary'],color='mediumseagreen', label='Cluster 4')\n",
    "ax.scatter(centers[:,0], centers[:,1], centers[:,2], s = 250, c = 'k', marker='*', label = 'Centroid')\n",
    "plt.legend(loc='center left',markerscale=2)\n",
    "plt.title('3D Customer Segmentation', pad = 15)\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Recency', labelpad = 15)\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Frequency', labelpad = 15)\n",
    "ax.set_zlabel('Monetary')\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "40d61850",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Conclusion Customer Segmentation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f4724f18",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "* 1. Cluster 1 is our <b>Promising Customers</b>\n",
    "\n",
    "Promising customers are customers who have been shopping recently, but the frequency and amount of money spent in our stores is still small or below average. Create brand awareness and provide discounts.\n",
    "* 2. Cluster 2 is our <b>Lost Customers</b>\n",
    "\n",
    "Lost customers are customers who have not been shopping for a long time, and the frequency and amount of money spent is also very low. Revive their interest with reach out campaign, ignore otherwise.\n",
    "* 3. Cluster 3 is our <b>Champion Customers</b>\n",
    "\n",
    "Champion customers are the best customers, new buyers, most frequently, and are heavy buyers. Reward this customer. They can be early adopters for new products and will help promote your brand\n",
    "* 4. Cluster 4 is our <b>At Risk Customers</b>\n",
    "\n",
    "At Risk Customers are customers who often buy and spend a lot of money, but haven't been shopping recently. We can provide offers or discounts to these customers, so that they are interested in shopping again at our store."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f24c3f2d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "- **Support**:It measures the percentage of itemset occurrence in all transactions.\n",
    "![image](https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/1c6acacd3b17051205704b5d323c83fc737e5db1)\n",
    "- **Confidence**: Confidence measures how strong the association rule is. How often item Y appears in the purchase transaction of item X.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "![image](https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/90324dedc399441696116eed3658fd17c5da4329)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "87a56f6c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "- **Lift**: Lift of the rule is defined as the ratio of observed support to the support expected in the case the elements of the rule were independent. Lift values > 1 are generally more “interesting” and could be indicative of a useful rule pattern.\n",
    "![image](https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/c392e3111167b60687405dfdc7ed55f22409f4c5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bc5972bb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Conclusion**\n",
    "\n",
    "As we have seen, the generation of rules is a very simple process, but very computationally expensive, since it grows exponentially with the increase of the set of items.\n",
    "\n",
    "Overall, we seek the proper balance between support and confidence leading to a reasonable number of strong rules.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the other hand, if the goal is to identify rare but with high confidence patterns, we should proceed as previously, by establishing a low level of support and a higher level of confidence, which leads to a large number of rules.\n",
    "\n",
    "With this in mind, the rules with low support and high confidence would then be our target for further study and than outlining of strategies to raise cross selling."
   ]
  },
